truggles to represent is disappearing.Working Skin develops this argument by exploring the interconnected work of tanners in Japan, Buraku rights activists and their South Asian allies, as well as cattle ranchers in West Texas, United Nations officials, and international NGO advocates. Moving deftly across these engagements, Joseph Hankins analyzes the global political and economic demands of the labor of multiculturalism. Written in accessible prose, this book speaks to larger theoretical debates in critical anthropology, Asian and cultural studies, and examinations of liberalism and empire, and it will appeal to audiences interested in social movements, stigmatization, and the overlapping circulation of language, politics, and capital.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBuraku peoplexGovernment policy. 0aBuraku peoplexSocial conditions. 0aLaborxJapan. 0aLaborzJapan. 0aMulticulturalismxJapan. 0aMulticulturalismzJapan. 0aWorking classxJapan. 0aWorking classzJapan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095916340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959163423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959163/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles